{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS 1 review (G6 — approach soundness):\n\nAffirmations: mechanism is verified sound against the codebase. `process_snapshot` (src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py:515) restores every compiled_state key, and `compact.py:92,129` builds the SNAPSHOT compiled_state via `reduce_ticket` — so placing `managed_refs` in compiled_state does survive compaction for free, exactly as claimed (solves the named problem, not a proxy). The fail-closed empty-default gate doubling as the back-out posture is good edge handling, and the deferred-reclamation rationale (peer-snapshot required, prune-vs-fold hazard avoided) is strong mechanism reasoning. Positive rationale for choosing compiled_state-fold over the `local_label_intent`-style projection is present and load-bearing.\n\nOne coaching finding on a load-bearing ordering detail (migration-seeding):\n\n- [ ] Specify exactly WHERE in the reduce pipeline the migration-seed fires when `managed_refs` is absent (initial state init vs. at `process_snapshot` when the key is missing vs. a post-replay finalize step) and how it composes with the incremental monotonic fold during a FULL replay. During replay, `managed_refs` is absent at the start and deps/parent are built up incrementally by process_create/process_link; a seed keyed on \"current deps + parent_id\" fired at the wrong point could either double-seed or, worse, mask a genuine pre-snapshot UNLINK (resurrecting a ref the operator removed). Add an AC/test asserting the seed fires only on the no-managed_refs branch and does NOT re-add a ref unlinked before the seeding point. (criteria: G6)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782538464558535001,"uuid":"8d6f4d40-bb80-4a8f-91cb-d20cc6777505"}